\f0\b\fs40 \cf0 c27 Forms of Consciousness\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs26 \cf0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 Below is a compact catalogue of the most frequently cited \'93forms\'94 or \'93types\'94 of consciousness that scholars typically enumerate when they talk about \'93more than one hard problem.\'94 Different authors group them slightly differently, so the exact count varies (most lists land between\uc0\u8239 18\u8239 and\u8239 27). I\'92ve gathered the most common entries from philosophy, cognitive neuroscience, and comparative\u8209 animal work, arranging them into four broad families for clarity.\
\
\pard\pardeftab560\sa40\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 1. Phenomenal / Qualitative Forms\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs26 \cf0 {\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Visual consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 experience of colour, shape, motion, depth.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Auditory consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 hearing tones, speech, spatial sound.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Somatosensory consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 touch, temperature, pain.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Olfactory consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 smell.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Gustatory consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 taste.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Interoceptive consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 awareness of internal bodily states (heartbeat, hunger, thirst).\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Emotional consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 feeling states such as joy, fear, shame.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf0 (These seven capture the distinct qualia associated with each sensory or affective channel.)
\f1\i0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab560\sa40\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 2. Levels / Degrees of Awareness\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs26 \cf0 {\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Arousal / vigilance
\f1\b0  \'96 basic wakefulness versus deep sleep/coma.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Perceptual consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 being aware of specific external stimuli.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Self\uc0\u8209 recognition
\f1\b0  \'96 recognizing oneself as the subject (mirror test, \'93I\'94 sense).\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Meta\uc0\u8209 consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 reflecting on one\'92s own mental states (\'93thinking about thinking\'94).\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Narrative / autobiographical consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 constructing a continuous self\uc0\u8209 story over time.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
\cf0 \
\pard\pardeftab560\sa40\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 3. Functional / Theoretical Sub\uc0\u8209 components\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls3\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs26 \cf0 {\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Integrated Information (\uc0\u934 )
\f1\b0  \'96 the amount of information that is both differentiated and unified (IIT).\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Global Workspace broadcasting
\f1\b0  \'96 information that becomes globally available for report and control (GWT).\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Higher\uc0\u8209 Order Thought (HOT)
\f1\b0  \'96 a first\uc0\u8209 order mental state that is the target of a higher\u8209 order representation.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Predictive\uc0\u8209 coding / Bayesian inference
\f1\b0  \'96 conscious experience as the brain\'92s best prediction of sensory input (Predictive Processing).\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Recurrent processing
\f1\b0  \'96 sustained reverberation of activity within cortical loops (Recurrent\uc0\u8209 processing theory).\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0

\f2\i \cf0 (These are not \'93modalities\'94 per se but distinct mechanistic ingredients that many theories treat as necessary for consciousness.)
\f1\i0 \
\
\pard\pardeftab560\sa40\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs32 \cf0 4. Species\uc0\u8209 Specific / Developmental / Contextual Forms\
\pard\pardeftab560\pardirnatural\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b0\fs26 \cf0 {\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Primary (non\uc0\u8209 reflective) consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 basic perceptual awareness found in many vertebrates and some invertebrates.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Reflective (higher\uc0\u8209 order) consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 capacity for introspection, largely human (some evidence in great apes).\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Collective / swarm consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 emergent shared informational states in highly coordinated groups (e.g., ant colonies, bird flocks).\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Artificial / synthetic consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 hypothesized conscious states that could arise in sufficiently complex AI architectures.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Dream consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 vivid phenomenology without external sensory input, altered self\uc0\u8209 awareness.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Lucid\uc0\u8209 dream consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 dream experience combined with meta\uc0\u8209 awareness that one is dreaming.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Locked\uc0\u8209 in consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 preserved phenomenal experience despite severe motor paralysis.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Blindsight consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 residual visual processing without accompanying phenomenology (illustrates dissociation).\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Split\uc0\u8209 brain consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 two semi\uc0\u8209 independent streams of awareness in each cerebral hemisphere after corpus callosum severance.\
{\listtext	0.	}
\f0\b Altered\uc0\u8209 state consciousness
\f1\b0  \'96 experiences under psychedelics, meditation, or anesthesia that differ qualitatively from ordinary waking consciousness.\
\pard\pardeftab560\slleading20\partightenfactor0
